		<header>
			
			<h1>Nigeria implements import duty reforms to promote cassava flour use</h1>

			
			<h4>
												09 September 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In July 2012, the Nigerian government moved ahead with reforms to import duties with a view to promoting greater use of cassava flour in bread. It is ‘reducing the duty on cassava enhancing enzymes from 10 per cent to zero per cent’ and on 1 July imposed an additional 15% duty on imported wheat, taking it to 20%. A level of 65% on wheat flour is also to be introduced, with revenues being used to ‘create a Cassava Bread Development Fund’, to finance the necessary investments to convert to blended wheat/cassava flour use (research, training, experimentation, re-equipping).</p><p>The Federal Government’s policy on blending cassava flour with wheat flour in bread making is causing considerable controversy, with opinions being expressed in local newspapers that ‘cassava bread is an idea whose time has not yet arrived’. It is argued that a typical Nigerian bakery would have to make changes to its current production practices to come in line with government requirements for blending of cassava flour in bread, necessitating large-scale retraining of staff.</p><p>While Nigeria is the largest global producer of cassava, it is argued that the required expansion of cassava production to meet government blending targets is ‘not feasible’ in the short term, particularly given political unrest in the northern part of Nigeria. This, it is argued, could lead to serious supply problems. The ministerial announcement that a deal to export 1 million tonnes of cassava chips valued at US$136 million to China had been concluded could add to national supply problems, given the competing uses to which cassava can be put (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Cereals/Development-of-cassava-value-chain-seen-as-means-of-reducing-Nigeria-s-food-import-bill" target="_blank">Development of cassava value chain seen as means of reducing Nigeria’s f...</a>’, 16 January 2012).</p><p>The effects of the new measures introduced appear to have already had an impact, with the Association of Master Bakers and Caterers of Nigeria in mid July announcing a 20% increase in bread prices, following the introduction of an additional 15% duty on imported wheat. However, record high global prices could also be a contributing factor to local price rises (see <i>Agritrad</i>e article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Cereals/Sharp-fall-in-world-cereals-production-forecast" target="_blank">Sharp fall in world cereals production forecast</a>’, 9 September 2012).</p><p>Dr Akinwumi Adesina, the Nigerian Minister of Agriculture and Rural Development, has claimed that the flour milling industry ‘was bent on undermining the efforts of the Federal Government’ to promote greater use of cassava flour in bread, with the government now ‘importing 18 quality cassava mills from China to …break the monopoly of flour millers’.</p>
		
		
