<a href="http://www.agrimoney.com/marketreport/morning-markets-corn-soybean-prices-climb-to-record-highs--1705.html" target="_self">http://www.agrimoney.com/marketreport/morning-markets-corn-soybean-price...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Nigeria is currently the largest producer of cassava in the world, with an annual output of 34 million tonnes. Cassava plays a dominant role in the rural economy of the southern agro-ecological zones and in increasingly gaining importance in other areas of Nigeria. In the past 20 years, both yields and the area under cassava have expanded, supported by a relatively well developed marketing infrastructure, technological improvements in processing, the large internal market and the many uses to which cassava can be put.</p><p>The current initiative, however, needs to be seen in the context not only of the retooling and retraining needs faced in servicing the Nigerian bakery sector, but also of the earlier failure of similar initiatives, which would appear to be holding back new investment.</p><p>One of the most immediate effects of the tariff increases on wheat is likely to be the encouragement of smuggling. In this context the Nigerian government may need to consider a more nuanced use of trade policy tools, to encourage changes in corporate practices (for example, the use of reduced tariff access to wheat imports for individual users linked to the attainment of government blending targets). However this more nuanced use of trade policy tools could well run up against governance constraints.</p>
		</div>
		
